(1.1) White noise

t <- 1:365
x <- rexp(365, 1)
mod <- lm(x~t)
r <- mod$residuals
rt <- ts(r)
plot(x)

xt <- ts(x)
plot.ts(xt)

dt <- diff(x, 3)
plot.ts(dt)

plot.ts(rt)

w = rnorm(50,0,1) # 500 N(0,1) variates
plot.ts(w, main="white noise")

acf(w, lag.max = 20)

Moving Average

rr w = rnorm(500,0,1) # 500 N(0,1) variates v = filter(w, sides = 2, filter=rep(1/3,3)) # moving average par(mfrow=c(2,1)) #only allows two plots to be shown at a time plot.ts(w, main=noise) # original white noise plot.ts(v, ylim=c(-3,3), main=average) # moving average plot

Random Walk with Drift

rr set.seed(154) # so you can reproduce the results w = rnorm(200); x = cumsum(w) # two commands in one line wd = w +.2; xd = cumsum(wd) # .2 adds the drift plot.ts(xd, ylim=c(-5,55), main=walk, ylab=) #random walk plotted alone with drift lines(x, col=4); abline(h=0, col=4, lty=2); abline(a=0, b=.2, lty=2) #plot of random walk with and without drift

Trigonometric Time Series Models

rr cs = 2cos(2pi1:500/50 + .6pi); w = rnorm(500,0,1) par(mfrow=c(3,1), mar=c(3,2,2,1), cex.main=1.5) plot.ts(cs, main=expression(2cos(2pit/50+.6pi))) plot.ts(cs+w, main=expression(2cos(2pit/50+.6pi) + N(0,1))) #signal to noise ratio increasing r plot.ts(cs+5w, main=expression(2cos(2pit/50+.6*pi) + N(0,25)))
